Key Learning Points
Authorization should never depend on the HTTP method.
Changing GET to POST (or vice versa) should never bypass security.
Always inspect administrator requests before attempting exploitation.
Test whether an endpoint behaves differently when using different HTTP methods.
A single change to the request method can expose serious authorization flaws.
Pentester's Perspective
Whenever you encounter an endpoint returning:

401 Unauthorized
or

403 Forbidden
ask yourself:

Does the application behave differently with another HTTP method?
Are authorization checks consistent across GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, and HEAD?
Can POST parameters be moved into the URL as GET parameters?
Does the server process the request differently depending on the method?
Changing the HTTP method is a simple but effective test during web application penetration testing. Although not as common as IDOR vulnerabilities, method-based authorization flaws can lead to critical privilege escalation when developers incorrectly associate security checks with specific HTTP methods.

